   TestCase Name: testmqtt_slow02

   Test Category: Slow MQTT

   Test Description:
   See what happens with slow subscribers and MaxMessage/DiscardMessage settings
   
   A few odd things about this test.  The goal is to fill the engine's internal 
   queue, and get thing going into a mode where the engine is discarding the 
   oldest messages in the queue, and then replacing with newer messages. 
   
   But at QoS=0, this is difficult. The engine does a 'fire and forget' and just
   keeps sending as fast as the transport layer will take messages.  
   The only way to fill that engine queue, is to first fill the socket buffer, 
   which causes the transport layer to send the engine a 'pause sending' request.
   It takes thousands of messages to fill the socket buffer. 
   
   And to cause the socket buffer to fill, you have to have a slow synchronous
   mqtt subscriber. 
   
   This test has two publishers and three subscibers as follows: 
   
   All three subscribers become active (cleanSession=0).
   
   Sub1 - is slow.he has a delay of 1 second every 100 messages. MaxMessages is 5000
   Sub2 - is not slow. But we are going to be sending fast enough
           to hopefully overfill his socketbuffer and engine queue. MaxMessages is 11,111
   Sub3 - is slow.he has a delay of 1 second every 50 messages. MaxMessages is 11,111 
   
   The two publishers start sending 120,000 messages each. (Pub 2 sends bigger messages).
   
   The slow consumers run until they have received 5,000 messages. 
   Sub2 runs until it gets 120,000 messages.  
   
   They then disconnect. And at that point, the engine queue MAY OR MAY NOT
   discard any queued messages. Usually it does, maybe because of timing 
   in the disconnect between the transport layer and the engine.  
   
   The two publishers then send another 50,000 messages each.  This will cause a 
   constant discarding of oldest messages to make room for newer messages. At the
   time the test was written, the engine was discard 5% of the MaxMessage size when
   it found that the queue full.  
   
   Then Pub1 sends 6,010 messages with a specific content. This should result in 
   a queue of messages that is between 95% of the MaxMessage size, and the MaxMessage
   size plus about 150. The exact number depends on a lot of variables, such as 
   how fast the socket buffer filled, and how fast the subscribers connected, whether the 
   engine queue was cleaned out when the subscribers disconnected, how fast is the network, 
   etc.. etc.. etc.. It is not possible to know how many will really be there, or 
   what order.. or how many got discarded because they were 'the oldest' when the 
   queue filled.  It's all a rather wild and hairy world at QoS=0.  
   
   However, the last 6010 should be the specific content sent last by Pub1. 
   
   The three publishers reconnect, and receive 95% of their MaxMessageSize. The
   last message received should be of that specific content type, which shows that
   the queue was indeed deleting older messages.  
   
   

  -->
  
